Wells or Saks Romer with his Fu Manchu super scientific villain. And in the pages of Argosy I discovered that this magazine, besides having westerns and romance and air war and whatnot, that they generally had some science fiction going. Some of the pioneer authors of Ray Cummings and R.F. Starzl and Victor Russo, and there was a lot of Burroughs, Mars and Venus and Pellucidar and those, and also in Blue Book Magazine. By 1930 we had about seven magazines. We had the amazing quarterlies in addition to the monthlies, and Science Wonder had come along, which also had a quarterly publication, and Air Wonder, and then there was Astounding Stories of Super Science started up, which is still going today under the modified title Analog Science Fiction. And that original amazing from April 1926 is still being published and in my collection. By 1929 a rather mundane mother began, had begun to be somewhat worried about my collecting instincts. She had counted my magazines, said, Son, do you realize you have 27 of these magazines? Now if you continue at that rate till you were a grown man, why, you might have 100 magazines. Well, my dear mother lived till nearly 94 and was in my own home at the end of her life. The home was now four stories, 17 rooms, three garages in which you couldn't park a toothpick, because we eliminated the cars from them and put in shelves, and that is totaled with the Science Fiction collections. As a matter of fact, whenever I see a garage sale nowadays, I buy another garage. I have two extra garages that are filling up around Los Angeles. So the collection has grown from that one single magazine back in October 1926. Here I am on the verge of my 55th anniversary in the field. Now there are 300,000 magazines and books and manuscripts and props from movies and artwork and stills. It's just, I stop at nothing, I even try to get space stamps from all over the world. I've been to Japan and if there's any greater collection, it must be underground or well hidden. Naturally, I'm so intensely interested in the subject matter that I seek out collectors everywhere in the world. There are maybe half a dozen of us who have equal collections of magazines, that is to say about 99% complete. And there are certainly collectors with enormous numbers of books. I've got to ask somebody to ask you. Okay. Mr. Ackerman, you're known as quite a fan, but to us collectors, you're also known as the ultimate collector. When did you start collecting science fiction, and what was your first goal, and how has that goal changed as far as what you're trying to collect? Well, in October 1926, when I first saw a science fiction magazine, I was only nine years old, and I don't believe I realized the periodicity of publications. I guess I thought it was some kind of a one-time phenomenon, and there would never be another amazing stories. And it wasn't until some months later in 1928 that I saw amazing stories again. Then I caught on to the fact that if I watched the newsstands carefully, about every four weeks, there would be more manna from heaven. So I read the magazine so quickly that there was nothing coming along for another month that I would re-read the stories. So I hung on to the magazines because they were very precious to me, and before I knew it, my mother said I had 27 of them. And by about 1930, I probably had around 100 of them. And one mad moment in my life, during the Depression, my parents persuaded me to sell my magazines in order to finance new ones, because 25 cents was kind of tough to come by when men were starving on the streets trying to make a living selling apples for a nickel. Well, I did sell my collection, such as it was, about 1930. And before their very eyes, my parents saw me becoming weak and waned and listless and lost my appetite. And about 48 hours was all I could take of that. So I said, okay, okay, you know, go and buy your magazines back if they mean so much to you. And from that day to this, I have never passed by a magazine. I just buy every single science fiction fantasy magazine as fast as they are published, have a standing order for every paperback to be sent to me, go through Publishers Weekly every seven days, and Locus and any source whatsoever that instances fantasy magazines and books, and send off for all of them. And then I go through catalogs from all over the world. And constantly mining the past, you would think that someday you'd say, well, I've got it all, but there just seems to be no end to it. A perfect example. I went to the World Science Fiction Convention down in Australia, walked a half a block from my hotel, and saw a science fiction book in a window. And I said, well, I don't have it. I suppose it was published here in Australia. But I went in and I found it was published in New York seven years earlier, and despite every review I'd read and every list I'd looked at, I hadn't known of it until that moment. So I feel my collection is incomplete if someone who's looking at it suddenly says, oh, don't you have? And then I've got 300,000 things, but I don't have this one particular magazine or book, so I guess I'll have to get it. How has where you've housed the collection through the years changed from your humble beginnings till now? Well, it started out in San Francisco. I had, down in the basement, my dad built me a little den, and I was able to keep everything in one very small room. Then when I moved back to Los Angeles where I was born, I lived with my maternal grandparents, and they had a rather large apartment plus three garages. That's where I started filling up garages. Before I knew it, they were full. And in the hallway in my maternal grandparents' home, I began stacking books up to the ceiling, and they gave me one bedroom. And pretty soon it was difficult even to get into bed because it was totally surrounded. I remember Life magazine came to me 30 years ago in 1951, took a photo of me in that bedroom. And in 1951, I finally moved into my first home. That had 13 rooms and three garages. And when I totaled that, and I really mean totaled it, used as many drawers as weren't absolutely necessary for clothing. They had books and magazines and put them under the beds. And we didn't need all the bathrooms, so I filled those. And finally, when my wife, the university professor and science fiction translator, came home and looked in the refrigerator one day and found the food was gone, replaced by reels of science fiction movies, she realized the end had come for that home. So for a couple of years, we lived in an apartment while I used a 13-room home and three garages totally for my collection. We started all over again eight years ago with a four-story, 17-room home and the usual three garages. And now that's bursting at the seams, and I've added two garages that I'm renting around town. Fortunately, the mayor of Los Angeles has come to my rescue. He discovered me, came out to the house, had four librarians come and look at everything, and they estimated there are approximately 300,000 pieces in the collection. And the city of Los Angeles in the near future is going to create an actual museum. It won't just be a wing of the library or anything of that sort, but an actual bonafide science fiction museum that already, when you're three blocks away, the structure of it will tell the story. It's just, hey, that's got to be the museum. And the grandson of Edgar Rice Burroughs has already indicated to me when the museum exists, that he'd be very happy to have an Edgar Rice Burroughs wing in it and make all of the first editions available and manuscripts and the artwork by J. Allen, St. John and others. And I think that Hollywood will very much get into the act once it exists. And in addition to the props I've been able to acquire on my own, like Bela Lugosi's Dracula cape and Lon Chaney Sr.'s makeup kit and Life Masks of Karloff and Peter Lorre and John Carradine and Vincent Price and many of the animated monsters from King Kong and Harryhausen films that I imagine the Star Wars people and Alien and so on, they will be all quick to contribute because everybody will want to be represented in something that is available to the public seven days a week, people for all over the world to come and see something like Disneyland and Magic Castle and Universal Tour and so on. Is this something that the City of Los Angeles will sponsor entirely? Well, I think it will be in two parts. About the 15th of September, I'm going to go down to the mayor's office. They tell me that they have found a benefactor who is going to create a cultural center and make the museum a centerpiece of it. It will be one thing just to move it out of my home. They estimate it will take $125,000 just to move it to its final resting place. And surely it costs multi-millions of dollars for the museum itself. And I don't want it just frozen. The day I give it away, that's it. It never grows. I hope that 200 years after I'm gone that it will still be up to date that all the magazines and books and posters and everything will be added. I think the city feels its responsibility will be to create the housing for it originally. And then they hope to institute what they call a support committee. that they're going to invite Robert Block, A. E. Van Vogt, Ray Bradbury, Steven Spielberg, Steven King, George Lucas, John Landis, maybe way over there in Sri Lanka, Arthur C. Clarke, all the independently wealthy science fiction practitioners to see if they would like to pitch in. For instance, George Lucas, I think, gave something like a million and a half recently to the university where he had graduated. So some of these high-powered, financially set people will get in the act and contribute. they'll be the sponsoring committee to make it possible to go on adding to it. I would like to see a theater in conjunction with it where you'd be seeing all the classic movies constantly and to have a fund that I might mastermind as the curator to purchase fine artwork and something that we should have in such a collection. For instance, the first edition of Frankenstein, which is rather difficult to come by because it wasn't a single book, it was three books. And I think at the present time I know of a set that's around 4,500. And something like the autograph of Edgar Allan Poe ought to be in the collection. Fortunately, I do have Wells' autograph because I saw him in person and shook hands with him. And I've been able to acquire the signature of Mary Shelley, who wrote Frankenstein, and have a letter by Jules Verne. But these really costly things is going to have to be people like those I just instanced that will be able to finance him. Okay. That's all I have. That's all I have, too. Okay. I remember reading through the magazines and whatnot your efforts to get all this, your museum, the museum started, you know, so there would be a permanent place to collect those. When you get it all moved out of your 17-room house, you know, the wall, you see actual walls in the house. Yeah. Or you've got to start at the first spot on the first of the shelf and go out and click book one and start filling it up again. Well, I really won't need a 17-room home anymore. You know, I'll be 65 in a few months and before I turn around I'll be 70. And obviously nearer the end of my life than the beginning, so we'll kind of cool it and get a more modest home for the last years of our life. But I'll always want a guest room and I think I'm always going to keep several hundred really favorite things around me, my best books. Your wife must have been very understanding through these years. Well, fortunately, she was a science fiction fan all of her life before she met up with me, only she was a fan in French and German. And when she came to this country around 33 years ago, she gravitated toward becoming a book clerk. And one day I walked up to her with a whole stack of books to buy and she said, may I wait on you, sir? And that was her fatal mistake. I've been doing so ever since. May I get you to sign my program? Sure. Your autograph is going to be...

Mr. Ackerman, you're known as quite a fan, but to us collectors, you're also known as the
ultimate collector.
When did you start collecting science fiction, and what was your first goal, and how has that
goal changed as far as what you're trying to collect?
Well, in October 1926, when I first saw a science fiction magazine, I was only nine years old, and I don't believe I realized the periodicity of publications.
I guess I thought it was some kind of a one-time phenomenon, and there would never be another amazing stories.
And it wasn't until some months later in 1928 that I saw amazing stories again.
Then I caught on to the fact that if I watched the newsstands carefully, about every four weeks, there would be more manna from heaven.
So I read the magazine so quickly that there was nothing coming along for another month that I would re-read the stories.
So I hung on to the magazines because they were very precious to me, and before I knew it, my mother said I had 27 of them.
And by about 1930, I probably had around 100 of them.
And one mad moment in my life, during the Depression, my parents persuaded me to sell my magazines in order to finance new ones,
because 25 cents was kind of tough to come by when men were starving on the streets trying to make a living selling apples for a nickel.
Well, I did sell my collection, such as it was, about 1930.
And before their very eyes, my parents saw me becoming weak and waned and listless and lost my appetite.
And about 48 hours was all I could take of that.
So I said, okay, okay, you know, go and buy your magazines back if they mean so much to you.
And from that day to this, I have never passed by a magazine.
I just buy every single science fiction fantasy magazine as fast as they are published,
have a standing order for every paperback to be sent to me,
go through Publishers Weekly every seven days, and Locus and any source whatsoever that instances fantasy magazines and books,
and send off for all of them. And then I go through catalogs from all over the world.
And constantly mining the past, you would think that someday you'd say, well, I've got it all, but there just seems to be no end to it.
A perfect example. I went to the World Science Fiction Convention down in Australia,
walked a half a block from my hotel, and saw a science fiction book in a window.
And I said, well, I don't have it. I suppose it was published here in Australia.
But I went in and I found it was published in New York seven years earlier,
and despite every review I'd read and every list I'd looked at, I hadn't known of it until that moment.
So I feel my collection is incomplete if someone who's looking at it suddenly says, oh, don't you have?
And then I've got 300,000 things, but I don't have this one particular magazine or book, so I guess I'll have to get it.
How has where you've housed the collection through the years changed from your humble beginnings till now?
Well, it started out in San Francisco. I had, down in the basement, my dad built me a little den,
and I was able to keep everything in one very small room.
Then when I moved back to Los Angeles where I was born, I lived with my maternal grandparents,
and they had a rather large apartment plus three garages.
That's where I started filling up garages. Before I knew it, they were full.
And in the hallway in my maternal grandparents' home, I began stacking books up to the ceiling,
and they gave me one bedroom. And pretty soon it was difficult even to get into bed because it was totally surrounded.
I remember Life magazine came to me 30 years ago in 1951, took a photo of me in that bedroom.
And in 1951, I finally moved into my first home. That had 13 rooms and three garages.
And when I totaled that, and I really mean totaled it, used as many drawers as weren't absolutely necessary for clothing.
They had books and magazines and put them under the beds. And we didn't need all the bathrooms, so I filled those.
And finally, when my wife, the university professor and science fiction translator, came home and looked in the refrigerator one day
and found the food was gone, replaced by reels of science fiction movies, she realized the end had come for that home.
So for a couple of years, we lived in an apartment while I used a 13-room home and three garages totally for my collection.
We started all over again eight years ago with a four-story, 17-room home and the usual three garages.
And now that's bursting at the seams, and I've added two garages that I'm renting around town.
Fortunately, the mayor of Los Angeles has come to my rescue. He discovered me, came out to the house,
had four librarians come and look at everything, and they estimated there are approximately 300,000 pieces in the collection.
And the city of Los Angeles in the near future is going to create an actual museum.
It won't just be a wing of the library or anything of that sort, but an actual bonafide science fiction museum
that already, when you're three blocks away, the structure of it will tell the story.
It's just, hey, that's got to be the museum. And the grandson of Edgar Rice Burroughs has already indicated to me
when the museum exists, that he'd be very happy to have an Edgar Rice Burroughs wing in it
and make all of the first editions available and manuscripts and the artwork by J. Allen, St. John and others.
And I think that Hollywood will very much get into the act once it exists.
And in addition to the props I've been able to acquire on my own, like Bela Lugosi's Dracula cape and Lon Chaney Sr.'s makeup kit
and Life Masks of Karloff and Peter Lorre and John Carradine and Vincent Price
and many of the animated monsters from King Kong and Harryhausen films that I imagine the Star Wars people
and Alien and so on, they will be all quick to contribute because everybody will want to be represented
in something that is available to the public seven days a week, people for all over the world to come and see something like Disneyland
and Magic Castle and Universal Tour and so on.
Is this something that the City of Los Angeles will sponsor entirely?
Well, I think it will be in two parts. About the 15th of September, I'm going to go down to the mayor's office.
They tell me that they have found a benefactor who is going to create a cultural center
and make the museum a centerpiece of it.
It will be one thing just to move it out of my home.
They estimate it will take $125,000 just to move it to its final resting place.
And surely it costs multi-millions of dollars for the museum itself.
And I don't want it just frozen. The day I give it away, that's it. It never grows.
I hope that 200 years after I'm gone that it will still be up to date that all the magazines and books and posters
and everything will be added.
I think the city feels its responsibility will be to create the housing for it originally.
And then they hope to institute what they call a support committee.
that they're going to invite Robert Block, A. E. Van Vogt, Ray Bradbury, Steven Spielberg, Steven King, George Lucas, John Landis,
maybe way over there in Sri Lanka, Arthur C. Clarke, all the independently wealthy science fiction practitioners
to see if they would like to pitch in. For instance, George Lucas, I think, gave something like a million and a half recently
to the university where he had graduated.
So some of these high-powered, financially set people will get in the act and contribute.
they'll be the sponsoring committee to make it possible to go on adding to it.
I would like to see a theater in conjunction with it where you'd be seeing all the classic movies constantly
and to have a fund that I might mastermind as the curator to purchase fine artwork
and something that we should have in such a collection. For instance, the first edition of Frankenstein,
which is rather difficult to come by because it wasn't a single book, it was three books.
And I think at the present time I know of a set that's around 4,500.
And something like the autograph of Edgar Allan Poe ought to be in the collection.
Fortunately, I do have Wells' autograph because I saw him in person and shook hands with him.
And I've been able to acquire the signature of Mary Shelley, who wrote Frankenstein,
and have a letter by Jules Verne. But these really costly things is going to have to be people like those
I just instanced that will be able to finance him.
Okay. That's all I have.
That's all I have, too.
Okay.
I remember reading through the magazines and whatnot your efforts to get all this, your museum, the museum started, you know,
so there would be a permanent place to collect those.
When you get it all moved out of your 17-room house, you know, the wall, you see actual walls in the house.
Yeah.
Or you've got to start at the first spot on the first of the shelf and go out and click book one and start filling it up again.
Well, I really won't need a 17-room home anymore. You know, I'll be 65 in a few months and before I turn around I'll be 70.
And obviously nearer the end of my life than the beginning, so we'll kind of cool it and get a more modest home for the last years of our life.
But I'll always want a guest room and I think I'm always going to keep several hundred really favorite things around me, my best books.
Your wife must have been very understanding through these years.
Well, fortunately, she was a science fiction fan all of her life before she met up with me, only she was a fan in French and German.
And when she came to this country around 33 years ago, she gravitated toward becoming a book clerk.
And one day I walked up to her with a whole stack of books to buy and she said, may I wait on you, sir?
And that was her fatal mistake. I've been doing so ever since.
May I get you to sign my program?
Sure.
Your autograph is going to be...
